
'''''The Newton Letter''''' is a novel by [[John Banville]], first published in 1982. It was published in the [[United States]] in 1987. Drawing comparisons with [[Ford Madox Ford]]'s ''[[The Good Soldier]]'' and [[John Hawkes (novelist)|John Hawkes]]'s ''[[The Blood Oranges]]'' for their use of the [[unreliable narrator]], ''The Newton Letter'' was described there as Banville's "most impressive work to date".<ref name=nyt/>

The book opens with: "Words fail me."<ref>{{cite news|first=Thomas|last=O'Dwyer|url=http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/jpost/access/99739473.html?dids=99739473:99739473&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Apr+30%2C+1993&author=Thomas+O'Dwyer&pub=Jerusalem+Post&desc=EMERALD+ISLE+GEMS&pqatl=google|title=Emerald Isle Gems|newspaper=[[The Jerusalem Post]]|date=30 April 1993}}</ref> It follows the adventures of an aspiring biographer of [[Isaac Newton]] who rents a rural retreat in the south of Ireland. He becomes involved with two women: Charlotte and Ottilie. Charlotte's husband, Edward, also appears. It has been observed that Charlotte, Ottilie and Edward are the three main characters of [[Johann Wolfgang von Goethe|Goethe]]'s 1809 novel ''[[Elective Affinities]]''.<ref name=nyt>{{cite news|first=Molly|last=Hite|url=http://www.nytimes.com/books/99/06/20/nnp/banville-newton.html|title=Taken for Patricians|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=19 July 1987}}</ref>

''The Newton Letter'' is the third of Banville's "scientific tetralogy" and the writer has recommended those who wish to sample his work to begin with it, saying: "It's pretty well all there. And it's short."<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/books/2008/jun/10/johnbanville|title=John Banville: Recommended works|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref>

